**Abstract:**
Brief philosophical notes dated January 26, 1993, examining authorial voice and perspective in philosophy. The document contrasts first-person and third-person philosophical writing (Kant/Descartes vs. Skinner), then distinguishes the exposed subject's perspective from the pure contemplator's perspective. It identifies two fundamental modes: curiosity (whose purpose is to know) and concern (whose purpose is to change the world to which a subject is exposed).

**AI Recommendation:** Methodological notes on philosophical perspective; develops key distinction between exposed subject and contemplator.

